TY  - JOUR
T1  - Change and Development in a Pluralistic World: the View From the Classics
AU  - Kilduff, Martin
AU  - Dougherty, Deborah
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2000.3707717
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2000.3707717
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 777
EP  - 782
VL  - 25
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - The study of the classics in our field is important to the themes of this special issue because (1) the classics have shaped the world we live in; (2) studying the classics enlarges our theoretical alternatives; and (3) the critique of taken-for-granted assumptions enshrined in the classics can spur change, development, and pluralism. We briefly review a selection of classic writings to illustrate how change and pluralism have been presented as threats, as opportunities for the management of innovation, and as intrinsic aspects of management.
AB  - The study of the classics in our field is important to the themes of this special issue because (1) the classics have shaped the world we live in; (2) studying the classics enlarges our theoretical alternatives; and (3) the critique of taken-for-granted assumptions enshrined in the classics can spur change, development, and pluralism. We briefly review a selection of classic writings to illustrate how change and pluralism have been presented as threats, as opportunities for the management of innovation, and as intrinsic aspects of management.
