T1  - Trust and Adaptation in Relational Contracting
AU  - Jeffries, Frank L.
AU  - Reed, Richard
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2000.3707747
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2000.3707747
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 873
EP  - 882
VL  - 25
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Trust, which occurs at the organizational and interpersonal levels, is generally believed to be important for the success ol interfirm relationships. We explore the effects of interaction between the two types of trust on negotiators' motivation to solve problems of adaptation in relational contracting. What we find is that too much trust is as bad as too little. Solutions are furthest from optimal when both organizational and interpersonal trust are high or both are low.
AB  - Trust, which occurs at the organizational and interpersonal levels, is generally believed to be important for the success ol interfirm relationships. We explore the effects of interaction between the two types of trust on negotiators' motivation to solve problems of adaptation in relational contracting. What we find is that too much trust is as bad as too little. Solutions are furthest from optimal when both organizational and interpersonal trust are high or both are low.
