T1  - Exploring Paradox: Toward a More Comprehensive Guide
AU  - Lewis, Marianne W.
Y1  - 2000/10/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.2000.3707712
DO  - 10.5465/amr.2000.3707712
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 760
EP  - 776
VL  - 25
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - ?Paradox? appears increasingly in organization studies, often to describe conflicting demands, opposing perspectives, or seemingly illogical findings. This article helps researchers move beyond labeling?to explore paradoxes and contribute insights more in tune with organizational complexity and ambiguity. I first develop a framework that clarifies the nature of paradoxical tensions, reinforcing cycles, and their management. Using this framework, I then review studies in which paradoxes spurred by change and plurality are investigated. I conclude by outlining strategies for identifying and representing paradox, addressing implications for research.
